<div id="review_36552866" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/36552866" />
    <a title="Autumn" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/657683-autumn"><img alt="Autumn" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1239294995p2/657683.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/36552866?book_show_action=true">Oct 30, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Autumn" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Autumn" href="/user/show/657683-autumn">Autumn</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer36552866" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer914728292214223059">Alright, I&apos;ll say right up front that I would have given this book five stars, except that it has more profanity and school-boy crudities than I&apos;m comfortable with in a book. But, (and this might be a bad thing), I&apos;m willing to put up with a little more of that in a really great book. This book is definitely more PG13 than PG.<br/>That being said, it&apos;s a great story. It&apos;s set in a boys&apos; prep school in England and the story centers around Roy Straitley, a latin professor who has taught there for 33 ye</span>
  <span id="freeText914728292214223059" style="display:none">Alright, I'll say right up front that I would have given this book five stars, except that it has more profanity and school-boy crudities than I'm comfortable with in a book. But, (and this might be a bad thing), I'm willing to put up with a little more of that in a really great book. This book is definitely more PG13 than PG.<br />That being said, it's a great story. It's set in a boys' prep school in England and the story centers around Roy Straitley, a latin professor who has taught there for 33 years. Chapters are alternately told in his voice, and the voice of an unnamed new professor who plans to "take down" the school. We know from the outset that this new professor is planning murder and mayhem, but we don't know who he is or what he's planning to do. I love Straitley's wry sense of humor and his take on academic life. And the intended murder/mystery aspect is quite gripping. I finished the book sitting on the stairs by the kitchen while my kids ate breakfast one morning.<br /><br />PS - if you don't like profanity, don't look up the meaning to the latin phrases used by the students :) Just so you are forewarned...</span>
  <a data-text-id="914728292214223059" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


