<div id="review_117838893" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/117838893" />
    <a title="Monique" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1072826-monique"><img alt="Monique" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609173346p2/1072826.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/117838893?book_show_action=true">Aug 20, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Monique" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Monique" href="/user/show/1072826-monique">Monique</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1072826-monique?shelf=five-stars-best-i-ever-had">five-stars-best-i-ever-had</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1072826-monique?shelf=what-it-is-whats-up-mystery-novel">what-it-is-whats-up-mystery-novel</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer117838893" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15407715170836093205">Wow..what can I say about this book but I was blown away..Its an effort and exercise in vocabulary and patience but well worth it..The surprise twist that comes around page 324 is enough to make this book unforgettable and rare..This is the story of a prestigious all boys day school St. Oswalds and all the characters and secrets it holds are revealed to us by two narrators you love and hate... on one hand you have the loveable old Mr Straitley: a tweed jacket wearing relic of the old academic er</span>
  <span id="freeText15407715170836093205" style="display:none">Wow..what can I say about this book but I was blown away..Its an effort and exercise in vocabulary and patience but well worth it..The surprise twist that comes around page 324 is enough to make this book unforgettable and rare..This is the story of a prestigious all boys day school St. Oswalds and all the characters and secrets it holds are revealed to us by two narrators you love and hate... on one hand you have the loveable old Mr Straitley: a tweed jacket wearing relic of the old academic era when Latin was taught and respected instead of diminished by computer classes..Mr Straitley is cranky, pretentious, stubborn and silly but all in all my favorite teacher in a story as he is so richly drawn. The other narrator tells an alternate tale of St. Oswalds as they constantly feel excluded from the prestige and decorum of the school and so starts the obsessive and intriguing game of revenge and destruction starting with the faculty and unfortunately my Mr Straitley..I was caught up with this book for a week and actually found myself slowing down, rereading and relishing the language and prose of this talented author. She seamlessly intertwines Latin and GRE vocabulary words into a riveting tale with as I stated an amazing twist that made me want to reread the whole story again. I recommend this book to academic staff, aspiring writers, lovers of Latin and a good thrilling read..</span>
  <a data-text-id="15407715170836093205" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
