<span id="freeTextContainer11099427754436969052"><b>Rating: 4.5 stars</b><br/><br/>I really enjoyed this, it&apos;s different and quirky despite having dark undertones; the first line reads: &apos;If there&apos;s one thing I&apos;ve learned in the last fifteen years is that murder is really no big deal.&apos;<br/><br/>Roy Straitley has been the Latin Master at St Oswald&apos;s Grammar School for Boys for 33 years. Resistant to change, he&apos;s seen as a dinosaur to be humoured but ultimately removed, even though he still commands the respect of the boys and is dedicated to the school.<br/><br/>A new term brings n</span>
  <span id="freeText11099427754436969052" style="display:none"><b>Rating: 4.5 stars</b><br /><br />I really enjoyed this, it's different and quirky despite having dark undertones; the first line reads: 'If there's one thing I've learned in the last fifteen years is that murder is really no big deal.'<br /><br />Roy Straitley has been the Latin Master at St Oswald's Grammar School for Boys for 33 years. Resistant to change, he's seen as a dinosaur to be humoured but ultimately removed, even though he still commands the respect of the boys and is dedicated to the school.<br /><br />A new term brings new teachers, one of whom is full of cunning chaos, and so begins a game of cat and mouse between Roy and his nemesis. Teacher X is a former pupil who bears grudges and is out to destroy the school from within, not in one fell swoop, but piece by delicious piece. Told in alternating chapters by both teachers, the tale also visits the past where as a youngster, Teacher X yearns to fit in with the privileged boys but always feels like an outsider.<br /><br />This is well plotted and well observed. I loved Roy with his cranky dry wit and his weary but defiant views on modern life, and although I guessed X, it didn't detract from a very engaging and unconventional read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11099427754436969052" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

