<div id="review_1770057817" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1770057817" />
    <a title="Kyle" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9549139-kyle"><img alt="Kyle" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1595701516p2/9549139.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1770057817?book_show_action=true">Oct 19, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kyle" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kyle" href="/user/show/9549139-kyle">Kyle</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780060559151" href="/book/show/15108.Gentlemen_and_Players">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9549139-kyle?shelf=mystery-thriller">mystery-thriller</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1770057817" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer60505358579342069">From what started out as a neat premise quickly devolved into a tedious, meandering puddle of words. I will say this much, I was hooked from the beginning; The plot for revenge by an outcast antihero. Going back and forth in narration between the <b>PAWN</b>, our schemer (with trips back into the past, and present) and the <b>KING</b>, the &quot;Classics&quot; Master, old centurion Mr. Roy Straitley, we find ourselves as readers woven into the murky history of St. Oswald&apos;s school for boys, and the lengths some will go </span>
  <span id="freeText60505358579342069" style="display:none">From what started out as a neat premise quickly devolved into a tedious, meandering puddle of words. I will say this much, I was hooked from the beginning; The plot for revenge by an outcast antihero. Going back and forth in narration between the <b>PAWN</b>, our schemer (with trips back into the past, and present) and the <b>KING</b>, the "Classics" Master, old centurion Mr. Roy Straitley, we find ourselves as readers woven into the murky history of St. Oswald's school for boys, and the lengths some will go to to destroy or preserve it.<br /><br />The darker the subject matter got, the more I found myself enjoying it, but there were too few instances of truly rich and masterful revenge. Most of the time, the book was muddled down by its boring middle portion. The plot to slowly dismantle St. Oswald's by our devious perpetrator is a somewhat remarkable one, but lacks a certain finesse. And the motivations behind it are (to quote an important character) far too "banal." The incentive does not hold enough weight (in my eyes) for the ultimate modus operandi.<br /><br />Also, the twist that occurs during the climax happened to be one of the two routes I theorized it would go. The author does her best to throw you off, and had me thinking a third of the way through the novel that "there's no <i>way</i> that it could be..." But it turns out that it could, and it was. So, there was a sense of lacking any sort of powerful, shocking punch for me by the time the twist was revealed. By then, however, the book was starting to wind down. The ending dragged on and on, and just sort of fizzled out.<br /><br />Could a sequel be in the works? It's certainly a possibility given the circumstances of the ending. I doubt I'd give this story another go, though. All in all, it was a good book. I didn't loathe it, so that's a plus, but I didn't love it, either, and that disappoints me.</span>
  <a data-text-id="60505358579342069" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


